data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11 (Cosmos provider), the **sync-over-async opt-in is removed entirely**. The temporary escape hatch you configured in .NET 10 — typically something like:

```csharp
options.UseCosmos(...).AllowSynchronousIO()
```

— **no longer compiles or is ignored at runtime**. All synchronous LINQ operators (`ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`) and `SaveChanges()` on the Cosmos provider now throw **`InvalidOperationException`** unconditionally.

## What to do

Convert every synchronous call to its async counterpart:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
| Sync (broken) | Async (required) |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `await ToListAsync()` |
| `First()` | `await FirstAsync()` |
| `Count()` | `await CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `await SaveChangesAsync()` |

This also means **callers must go async** — the change propagates up the call stack (`async Task` all the way to the controller). Remove the old `AllowSynchronousIO` / `EnableSyncExecution` configuration since it no longer exists.
